Check Point Rises to 10-Year High as Israel-U.S. Index Gains

-- B y   T a l   B a r a k   H a r i f
-- 
2011-07-06T09:11:54Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-05/check-point-climbs-to-10-year-high-as-israeli-u-s-index-gains.html
Check Point Software Technologies
Ltd. (CHKP) , the world’s second-largest network-security company, rose
to the highest level in 10 years on bets clients will spend more
to defend their computer systems from hackers.  Check Point climbed 1.6 percent in Nasdaq Stock Market
trading yesterday to $57.65, the highest level since May 29,
2001. Shares of the Tel Aviv-based company have gained 97
percent over the past year compared with a 10 percent advance
for the Bloomberg Israel-US 25 Index of the largest Israeli-
based companies traded in New York.  Sony Corp.,  EBay Inc. (EBAY)  and government agencies ranging from
the Central Intelligence Agency to Arizona Department of Public
Safety have been targeted by hacker groups in recent months.
AntiSec, a computer hacking group, said on its Twitter feed over
the weekend that it accessed user names and passwords of a
server of Cupertino, California-based Apple Inc.  “When we are seeing some of these very transparent and
embarrassing security breaches, it will cause companies to take
a closer look at their strategy and can drive additional
spending,” said Gregg Moskowitz, an analyst at Cowen & Co. in
 New York . “We tend to see more fundamental upside for the stock
and expect to see it appreciate from where it is today.”  Check Point will probably report second-quarter adjusted
earnings-per-share of 66 cents per share on July 18, according
to the median estimate of 23 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg.  Bloomberg Israeli-US 25 Index  The Bloomberg Israel-US 25 Index gained 0.2 percent to
618.82 yesterday, the highest level since June 7, and is down
1.5 percent this year.  Israel ’s TA-25 Index fell 0.5 percent to
1,242.24 at 11:47 a.m. in Tel Aviv today. The Tel Aviv Stock
Exchange’s benchmark measure has lost 6.3 percent this year.  Alon Holdings Blue Square Ltd. (BSI) , the Rosh Ha’Ayin, Israel-
based operator of supermarkets and specialty stores, rose 4.1
percent to $8.45 in New York yesterday. In Israel today, the
shares fell 0.7 percent to 28.33 shekels, or the equivalent of
$8.29, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Protalix BioTherapeutics Inc. (PLX) , an Israeli biotechnology
company, climbed 3.5 percent to $6.53. The stock increased 1.8
percent to 22.08 shekels in Tel Aviv, or the equivalent of
$6.46, the data show.  Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd. (TEVA) , the world’s biggest
generic-drug company, fell 0.2 percent to $48.92 in New York.
The Israeli-traded shares dropped 0.3 percent to 166.20 shekels
today, or the equivalent of $48.61.  RADVision  RADVision Ltd. (RVSN)  sank 8.2 percent to $7.21, the lowest level
since Oct. 27. The maker of video-conferencing systems revised
its second-quarter loss estimate to at least 27 cents a share,
wider than the 12 cent average of two analyst estimates in a
Bloomberg survey. The stock lost 1.9 percent in  Tel Aviv  to
24.16 shekels, or the equivalent of $7.07, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  The shekel weakened for a third day today, falling 0.1
percent to 3.4193 per dollar. Israeli inflation-linked bonds
rose yesterday, pushing yields to the lowest level in three
weeks, after the utility authority said it may increase
electricity prices following the halt in natural-gas supplies
from  Egypt .  Morgan Stanley boosted its forecast for Israel’s economic
growth, saying that gross domestic product will climb 4.8
percent this year and 4 percent next year, according to an e-
mailed report dated July 1. The New York-based bank previously
had projected gains of 4.3 percent in 2011 and 3.5 percent in
2012.  To contact the reporter on this story:
